// 
// Beta 1958 - 1964, is a work by Victor Vasarely
// I found the existence of this piece in the book Vasarely, Magdalena Holzhey, p.10)
// However, there is little to no existence of this work that can be found online (at
// least from my research). I could only find some colored version on bidding websites,
// so I don't know about the authenticity of these pieces. While researching, I found
// a version I liked:
// https://www.amorosart.com/oeuvre-vasarely-objet_cin%C3%A9tique-71325.html
//
// It is labbeled "Objet Cinétique", and unfortunatly a lot of different pieces related 
// to Vasarely labelled "Objet Cinétique" can be found online. It is possible that this 
// version was from him, and likely that it was some recreation of his work Beta (this
// is a guess from me, I haven't verified this information).
//
// Vasarely wanted his work to be similar as music sheets,
// interpretable by anyone as they liked. He really wanted art to be more accessible,
// regardless of their background. I thought that recreating this particular version,
// that I liked more than his original work Beta, could be a great tribute to both 
// Beta and Vasarely's ideology.
//
// About the piece: since I diverged so much from the original work, I decided to try
// my best at recreating an accurate version of "Objet Cinétique".
//
//
// HOW TO LOOK AT THE PIECE
//
// This piece was made to be watched in full screen, by staring at the center for the
// whole duration of the animation. Due to how vision gets tricked in seeing a slow
// an continuous motion towards the center, the brain starts to have issues processing 
// the high contrast between the bands, and starts will feel incomfortable keeping the
// focus at the center. After 55s, once the motion stops, the piece reaches its final
// state, close to the version I tried to recreate. If the focus was kept at the center
// the work will seem to glitter because the brain still thinks there is motion and is
// lost by this static state. Bands becomes unstable. A weird feeling emerge when the
// brain realizes that nothing moves anymore, but the glitter will never trully stops.
// If you slightly look arround the center, the "disk" will appear to be rotating.
//
// Special Thanks to @FabriceNeyret2 for the time he took to review and optimize this
// shader. This version was re-written with his precious advice.
//



#define C_WIDTH_MIN .05
#define C_WIDTH_MAX .018
#define L_SMOOTH .15
#define PI 3.1415926

#define rot(a)   mat2( cos(a), -sin(a), sin(a), cos(a) )
#define rand(n)  fract(sin(dot(n, vec2(12.9898, 4.1414))) * 43758.5453)


void mainImage( out vec4 fragColor, in vec2 fragCoord )
{

    vec2 uv = (fragCoord - .5*iResolution.xy)  / iResolution.y;

    // piece is designed for 55s, t € [0;1]
    float t = min(1., iTime / 55.0);


    // space is divided into circles
   	float cwidth = mix(C_WIDTH_MIN, C_WIDTH_MAX, t);
    float dc = length(uv) / cwidth;

    // circle division
    float circ = abs(fract(dc) - .5);

    // the square
    vec2 v = smoothstep(0.27, 0.23, abs(uv) * rot(t * PI * 4.));
    float rect = pow(v.x* v.y, 10.);

    // the width of the circle line
    float width = 0.15 + 0.11 * rect;
    // we add some variation to it
    float ang = atan(uv.y, uv.x);
    float id = floor(dc);
    width+= cos(-id * .2 + ang*2. + t * 15.) * .05 + .05;

    // to match with our model, only 20 circles are visible
    if (dc > 21.) width = .3;


    // this isn't antialiasing, this was made to create moiré patterns, amplifying the illution of a motion 
    // having a constant value to smoothen is what makes the moiré works at any resolution, from my observations
    float c = smoothstep(width, width - L_SMOOTH, circ);

    // we cut outer ring
    c*= step(dc, 22.);

    // we cut a square out of this, and create a border arround it
    v = step(abs(uv), vec2(.4));
    float inside = v.x * v.y;
    v = step(abs(uv), vec2(.42));
    float border = v.x * v.y;
    c*= inside;
    c+= 1.0 - border;
    c+= .15 * rand(uv);

    // the background
    c*= clamp(pow(max(0., (1.-length(uv))), .2)* 1.1, .2, 1.);

    // Output to screen
    fragColor = c * vec4(1., 1., 0.92, 1.);
}
